    <text>
        <body>
            <head>1. Memorandum From <persName corresp="reciVADsSfCsRQoHd">Richard Pipes</persName>
                of the <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security Council</orgName>
                Staff to the Director of the <orgName corresp="reckjQkUajOv3dbTz">Arms Control and
                    Disarmament Agency</orgName> (<persName corresp="recM8U5HOaBRfTDmg"
                    >Rostow</persName>)<note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d1fn1">Source:
                    Reagan Library, <persName corresp="reccYhPleLdoqXAck">Matlock</persName> Files,
                        <gloss target="#t_USSR_1"><placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3"
                            >USSR</placeName></gloss>—<gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs
                            corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs></gloss> 1/2. Secret.
                    Sent through Allen, who did not initial the memorandum.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1981-07-29"
                        >July 29, 1981</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Preliminary <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O"
                            type="event">START</rs></gloss> Discussions</item>
            </list>
            <p>In accord with your wishes, here is a brief statement of my views on a possible
                opening phase of <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O"
                        type="event">START</rs></gloss>
                <note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d1fn2">In May 22 meeting of the <orgName
                        corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security Council</orgName>, Allen said:
                    “We’ve all been imprisoned by the <gloss target="#t_SALT_1"><rs
                            corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event">SALT</rs></gloss> language. We
                    need some new categories, e.g., <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event"
                        >Strategic Arms Reduction Talks</rs>. They would be known as <gloss
                        target="#t_START_1"><rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event"
                        >START</rs></gloss>.” See <ref target="frus1981-88v03#d56">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988 vol. III,
                            <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet Union</placeName>, January
                        1981–January 1983, Document 56</ref>.</note> consultations with the
                Russians, preceding the initiation of formal negotiations on <rs
                    corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k" type="topic">arms reductions</rs>. (S)</p>
            <p>
                <gloss target="#t_SALT_1"><rs corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event"
                    >SALT</rs></gloss> was a sort of bastard child of our short-lived love affair
                with the <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet Union</placeName>. One of its
                basic faults was that the theoretical premises of limiting nuclear arms were never
                analyzed: we simply adopted the <rs corresp="reccJaB2k7PllwmSp" type="topic"
                    >MAD</rs> doctrine, assumed the Russians shared it too, and proceeded to
                negotiate caps on launchers and <gloss target="#t_ABM_1"><rs
                        corresp="recXBtz7WTz23HoT0" type="topic">ABM</rs></gloss>. This hasty
                approach proved to have been most unfortunate. This time we may want to precede
                actual bean-counting exercises—which, according to your own testimony, may be months
                off—with semi-formal discussions with the Russians concerning some fundamentals, to
                wit:</p>
            <p>—Strategic doctrine.</p>
            <p>—Units of measurement of <rs corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms
                    control</rs>.</p>
            <p>—The data base and exchange of data <rs corresp="rect2ZBd3pFkOhBnq" type="topic"
                    >information</rs>.</p>
            <p>—<rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">Verification</rs>.</p>
            <p>—Means to improve prevention of accidental war. (S)</p>
            <pb facs="0031" n="2" xml:id="pg_2"/>
            <p>The advantages of this kind of exchanges, which could begin on short notice, would be
                two-fold:</p>
            <p>—One might learn something useful.</p>
            <p>—We would seize the initiative in <rs corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms
                    control</rs> talks and deflect some of the heat from us (especially if Moscow
                should refuse to participate in such an exchange of views). (S)</p>
            <p>My notion is that these talks would lead to no agreement: they would be meant to
                clarify our mutual approaches to issues that are indeed fundamental to effective <rs
                    corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms control</rs>. Participants should
                include high <rs corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms control</rs>
                representatives from both sides (but not the eventual negotiators) and have a set
                agenda lasting, say, something on the order of three to four weeks. (S)</p>
            <p>Carnes Lord concurs; <persName corresp="rectgZQLOFUiX9FUc">Robert
                    Schweitzer</persName> will comment separately.<note n="3" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d1fn3">Not found.</note>
            </p>
        </body>
    </text>
